<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">This is what the i=
nternet does. The corporation owning the platform provides users with a pub=
lication and distribution system in order to make a profit. Most do not off=
er editorial services, which does not mean they do not distribute the writi=
ng and thought of others for a profit. Many things that had been done by hu=
mans in the past are now done by machines and computers. But the distributi=
on of writing is the act of publishing, whether through bookstores or onlin=
e without providing any editorial service. They allow writers to access rea=
ders. Just because they provide technologies to distribute it does not chan=
ge the nature of the business.</p>
<hr>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0"><em>Question: Give=
n the number of governments that suppress free speech, there has to be a pl=
ace for anonymity.</em></p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Response: There ar=
e two problems with this view, from my point of view. The first is that in =
countries where there is censorship, there is the possibility that computer=
s might be seized and the writer taken away. This is far from certain, but =
in these countries prudent people know to take care of what they distribute=
. There is also a massive problem with anonymity: slander. On the internet =
it is easy to write untrue things meant to damage the reputation of another=
. Public figures in many places do not have the right in most circumstances=
 to file a civil suit against the sender. But the ordinary citizen who is s=
landered has the right to take civil action against the slanderer. This pro=
tection is essential in charging a person of (insert your favorite depravit=
y) with said depravity. If there is anonymity, then on the internet claims =
against you, for example, could be widely distributed without legal recours=
e. This could be done in ways that could not be traced to the source even w=
ith the cooperation of the system of distribution. There have been cases re=
levant to this. So while I understand the threat in oppressive nations, the=
 threat to reputation, the heart of the libel laws, is a very great threat =
on the internet, given anonymity. I would say on balance that this threat i=
s more likely and I think more common than the other, where the dangers are=
 well understood.</p>
<hr>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0"><em>Question: </em=
><em>An excellent statement of the ills that the internet has foisted upon =
us, but identity would drive away 90 percent (99 percent?) of internet user=
s. Not a bad thing but huge corporations are making gigantic sums of money =
off of aberrant behavior. Don=E2=80=99t you think they would lobby to defea=
t such a proposition if an attempt was made to legislate one?</em></p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Response: If most =
users on the internet would not be there if they had to take responsibility=
 for what they write, we should take a very careful look at the dangers tha=
t the internet poses. A better solution would be holding the publisher resp=
onsible for monitoring his technology =E2=80=93 in other words, by editing =
what is said. This would be a super opportunity for artificial intelligence=
 to prove me wrong about its limits.</p>
<hr>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0"><em>Question: </em=
><em>Anonymity is not the enemy of free speech =E2=80=93 it=E2=80=99s often=
 what makes genuine expression possible. The essence of free speech is spea=
king and standing by what you say. Don=E2=80=99t you think that accountabil=
ity should focus on unlawful content, not on revealing identity?</em></p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Response: The righ=
t to speech is a fundamental legal right in free nations. In my mind there =
is also responsibility in decent society to take responsibility for what yo=
u say. The nasty whisper, the false accusation, the claim of the other=E2=
=80=99s depravity, when untrue, is not protected in a free country, as it i=
s not in the United States. What makes a decent society is a citizenry that=
 says what it means and stands behind what it says. I have a suspicion that=
 when the founders added free speech to the Constitution, they had in mind =
the decency and courage to stand by what was said. If you have something to=
 say but do not want to be identified for saying it, I strongly suspect tha=
t you are about to say something you shouldn=E2=80=99t. The principle of fr=
ee speech and the willingness to hear a response or a counterargument are i=
n my mind linked. There is the right to free speech and then the moral prac=
tice of it, pompous as that sounds.</p>
<hr>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0"><em>Question: You =
sound like an old lady. Whenever something new comes along, there are alway=
s older people to say how terrible it is. </em></p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Response: The inte=
rnet is not a new technology. It was first introduced in the 1960s by the D=
epartment of Defense and was called ARPANET, for Advanced Research Projects=
 Agency Network, and was used for rapid communications between DoD research=
 centers. The first public internet services were introduced in the late 19=
80s and early 1990s with services companies such as Prodigy and CompuServe =
and the World Wide Web in 1991. So the technology is about 60 years old. Th=
e first commercial use was about 35 years ago. So if I sound like an old la=
dy, you... (deleted by my wife).</p>
<hr>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0"><em>Question: </em=
><em>You wrote: =E2=80=9CBut this is very far from the worst division in Am=
erican history. I would think Lincoln=E2=80=99s election that led to civil =
war was a couple notches above this. The division in the Great Depression w=
as far graver than this. The division in the 1970s over race and the Vietna=
m War, both frequently violent, was pretty bad. So I do not see the current=
 division as particularly worrisome. If we could get together after the Civ=
il War, the Great Depression, and the 1960s, we will get through this.=E2=
=80=9D </em></p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0"><em>All the exampl=
es you cite occurred when the U.S. empire&nbsp;was still expanding. The gro=
wing economy made it possible to&nbsp;=E2=80=9Cbuy peace.=E2=80=9D Today=E2=
=80=99s economy is&nbsp;more win-lose, with competing elites fighting over =
relatively scarcer resources.&nbsp;</em></p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Response: I do not=
 mean to dismiss your point, but I have to say that there is a constant dim=
ension of American culture that makes the assumption that the United States=
 is past its prime. By any measure it is not. The fact is that the American=
 GDP is one-quarter of the world=E2=80=99s economy, and that number is stab=
le (and extraordinary). To call that decline would be like saying that if R=
ome did not occupy another region each year it would be in decline. I know =
decline. The Chinese are far more worried about us than we are about them. =
That=E2=80=99s why they parade all of their new military technologies for t=
he world to see, while we evolve in secret. I could go on this way, but the=
 point I am making is that as I travel the world, the fundamental question =
citizens of every nation seem obsessed with is what will the United States =
do next. There is a belief in America, a constant feature of American histo=
ry, that our best days are over. This is not the perception I find in other=
 countries, except as hopes and prayers. Nor does America ever use the term=
 =E2=80=9Cempire,=E2=80=9D because we are not one. We are too indifferent t=
o the world to be an empire. The United States=E2=80=99 culture is to be bo=
th self-obsessed and profoundly self-critical. So I, with passion, must tak=
e issue with the assumption that remaining one-quarter of the world=E2=80=
=99s economy and not advancing to 30 percent means decline. But then this i=
s an American tradition, vastly underestimating our power.</p>
<hr>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0"><em>Question: </em=
><em>But before you publish your book, you DO get the input of your publish=
er and editor. And before you wrote your draft, you bounced those ideas off=
 colleagues, friends and family. Through all these means, you developed and=
 sharpened your thoughts. You are not held accountable for these conversati=
ons. You could have said some stupid things =E2=80=93 things you later chan=
ged your mind on as conversations continued. Those conversations are not pr=
eserved forever and broadcast to the world. They served a valuable function=
 in preparing you to say responsibly in book form what you eventually wrote=
.</em></p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Response: Publishe=
rs distribute books written by authors. Publishers are also responsible for=
 the books they sell, and can be sued for publishing libel, or simply held =
in contempt for allowing trash to be sold. The owners of the internet are p=
ublishers who distribute what is written. Yet they take no responsibility f=
or what they distribute and do not employ editors. They become wealthy none=
theless. They distribute the thoughts of others, do not edit out the trash,=
 and claim they are not responsible for any of this. I hold them responsibl=
e, but then, who am I?</p>

